"Dima M., Lohmann G.","Evidence for two distinct modes of large-scale ocean circulation changes over the last century",2010,"Journal of Climate","23","1",,"5","16",,,10.1175/2009JCLI2867.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77949337637&partnerID=40&md5=9a3a05b6969ead8ae87a395d2e9be6dc","Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research, Bremerhaven, Germany; Faculty of Physics, University of Bucharest, Bucharest, Romania","Dima, M., Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research, Bremerhaven, Germany, Faculty of Physics, University of Bucharest, Bucharest, Romania; Lohmann, G., Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research, Bremerhaven, Germany","Through its nonlinear dynamics and involvement in past abrupt climate shifts the thermohaline circulation (THC) represents a key element for the understanding of rapid climate changes. The expected THC weakening under global warming is characterized by large uncertainties, and it is therefore of significant importance to identify ocean circulation changes over the last century. By applying various statistical techniques on two global sea surface temperature datasets two THC-related modes are separated. The first one involves relatively slow adjustment of the whole conveyor belt circulation and has an interhemispherically symmetric pattern. The second mode is associated with the relatively fast adjustment of the North Atlantic overturning cell and has the seesaw structure. Based on the separation of these two patterns the authors show that the global conveyor has been weakening since the late 1930s and that the North Atlantic overturning cell suffered an abrupt shift around 1970. The distinction between the two modes provides also a new frame for interpreting past abrupt climate changes. © 2010 American Meteorological Society.",,"Abrupt climate change; Climate shifts; Conveyor belts; Data sets; Key elements; Non-linear dynamics; North Atlantic; Ocean circulation; Rapid climate change; Sea surface temperatures; Statistical techniques; Symmetric patterns; Thermohaline circulations; Atmospheric temperature; Belt conveyors; Global warming; Oceanography; climate change; data set; global warming; nonlinearity; overturn; sea surface temperature; thermohaline circulation; Atlantic Ocean; Atlantic Ocean (North)",,,,,,"Baines, P.G., Folland, C.K., Evidence for a rapid global climate shift across the late 1960s (2007) J. Climate, 20, pp. 2721-2744; Behl, R.J., Kennett, J.P., Brief interstadial events in the Santa Barbara basin, NE Pacific, during the past 60 kyr (1996) Nature, 379, pp. 243-246; Broecker, W.S., The biggest chill (1987) Nat. Hist., 96, pp. 74-82; Broecker, W.S., (1998) Paleocean circulation during the last deglaciation: A bipolar seesaw? Paleoceanography, 13, pp. 119-121; Bryden, H.L., Longworth, H.R., Cunningham, S.A., Slowing of the Atlantic meridional overturning circulation at 25°N (2005) Nature, 483, pp. 655-657; Cessi, P., Bryan, K., Zhang, R., Global seiching of thermocline waters between the Atlantic and the Indian-Pacific Ocean Basins (2004) Geophys. Res. Lett, 31, pp. L04302. , doi:10.1029/ 2003GL019091; Cronin, T.M., Dwyer, G.S., Kamiya, T.S., Schwede, S., Willard, D.A., Medieval warm period, Little Ice Age and 20th century temperature variability from Chesapeake Bay (2003) Global Planet. Change, 36, pp. 17-29; Crowley, T.J., North Atlantic Deep Water cools the Southern Hemisphere (1992) Paleoceanography, 7, pp. 489-497; Curry, R., Mauritzen, C., Dilution of the northern North Atlantic Ocean in recent decades (2005) Science, 308, pp. 1772-1774; Curry, R., Dickson, B., Yashayaev, I., A change in the freshwater balance of the Atlantic Ocean over the past four decades (2003) Nature, 426, pp. 826-829; Dansgaard, W., Evidence for general instability of past climate from a 250-kyr ice-core record (1993) Nature, 364, pp. 218-220; Deser, C., Blackmon, M.L., Surface climate variations over the North Atlantic Ocean during winter (1993) J. Cli